FINAL DECISION
This is the Final Decision on the petition of Superior Water, Light and Power Company 
(petitioner) for a declaratory ruling or, in the alternative, for approval of a holding company 
takeover.  The Commission DECLINES to issue a declaratory ruling as to whether or not the 
proposed acquisition of ALLETE, Inc. (ALLETE) requires approval under the Wisconsin Utility 
Holding Company Act, Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795 (WUHCA) and whether or not ALLETE and its 
holding company system would retain an exemption under the WUHCA following the 
acquisition.  
The petition for approval of a holding company takeover is APPROVED, subject to 
conditions.
Introduction
On July 19, 2024, the petitioner filed a petition for a declaratory ruling under Wis. Stat. 
¬ß 227.41 and Wis. Admin. Code ¬ß PSC 2.07, asking the Commission to issue two declaratory 
rulings in this proceeding.  The petitioner requested a declaratory ruling that the acquisition of 
the petitioner‚Äôs immediate corporate parent, ALLETE, by affiliates of Canada Pension Plan 
Investment Board (CPP Investments) and Global Infrastructure Managements, LLC, which 
operates under the trading name Global Infrastructure Partners (GIP, and together with CPP 
Investments, the Partners), does not require Commission approval under the WUHCA, by virtue PSC REF#:548255Public Service Commission of Wisconsin  
RECEIVED: 6/3/2025 3:25:01 PM
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
2of ALLETE‚Äôs exemption under subsection (8)(a) of the WUHCA.  The petitioner also sought a 
ruling stating that the proposed transaction would not affect any exemption ALLETE may hold 
under the WUHCA pursuant to Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(8)(a), and any such exemption would 
extend to ALLETE‚Äôs existing and future direct and indirect owners and affiliates.  ( PSC REF#: 
509235.)  In the alternative, if approval jurisdiction is asserted, the petitioner requested all 
necessary Commission approvals for the acquisition.
On September 12, 2024, Commission staff issued a memorandum for the Commission to 
consider the request to open a declaratory ruling proceeding.  ( PSC REF#: 516766.)  The 
Commission opened the docket to consider all or part of the declaratory ruling request and/or the 
request for alternative relief.  ( PSC REF#: 517297.)  On September 13, 2024, the Commission 
issued a Notice of Proceeding in this docket.  ( PSC REF#: 516931.)  The notice advised that a 
hearing would be scheduled at a later date.  The notice instructed those persons desiring to 
become a party to file for intervention no later than 14 days from the date of service.  The 
following organizations and entities requested and were granted intervention and are therefore 
parties to this proceeding: Citizens Utility Board of Wisconsin (CUB); International Brotherhood 
of Electrical Workers Local 31 (IBEW); Madison Gas and Electric Company (MGE); Wisconsin 
Electric Power Company (WEPCO); and Wisconsin Public Service Corporation (WPSC) 
(together with petitioner and ALLETE, parties).  ( PSC REF#: 530393.)  The parties for purposes 
of review under Wis. Stat. ¬ß¬ß 227.47 and 227.53, are listed in Appendix A.
On January 23, 2025, the parties filed a stipulation of facts and waiver of hearing.  
(PSC REF#: 530614.)  The parties agreed to waive their right to a hearing and stipulated to a set 
of uncontested facts for the purposes of this proceeding.  The uncontested facts reiterated the 
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
3details provided by the petitioner in this proceeding.  On February 11, 2025, the Partners filed an 
unopposed motion for full-party status.  ( PSC REF#: 532707.)  On February 11, 2025, 
Commission staff issued a memorandum analyzing the request and solicited comments from the 
parties and the public.  ( PSC REF#: 532758.)  Comments on the Commission staff memorandum 
were submitted by the petitioner, ALLETE, and the Partners ( PSC REF#: 534486), as well as 
joint comments from MGE, WEPCO, and WPSC.  ( PSC REF#: 534516.)  
On February 18, 2025, the Commission issued a Notice of Hearing scheduling a public 
hearing.  ( PSC REF#: 533718.)  Pursuant to due notice, on March 4, 2025, a hearing was held 
virtually for members of the general public.  The Commission‚Äôs public hearing process involved 
the opportunity for members of the public to submit written comments through the 
Commission‚Äôs website, or to testify at the public hearing.  The Commission received one 
comment from a member of the public.  ( PSC REF#: 535556.) 
The Commission discussed this matter at its open meeting of March 13, 2025. 
Findings of Fact
1. Petitioner is a ‚Äúpublic utility‚Äù as defined in Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.01(5) and a ‚Äúpublic 
utility affiliate‚Äù as defined in Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(1)(L).
2. ALLETE, as the owner of all of the voting securities of the petitioner, is a 
‚Äúholding company‚Äù as defined in Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(1)(h)1.a.
3. The proposed transaction, as conditioned by this Final Decision, is in the best 
interests of utility consumers, investors, and the public. 
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
4Conclusions of Law
1. The Commission has the jurisdiction and discretion to decline to issue a 
declaratory ruling pursuant to Wis. Stat. ¬ß¬ß 196.02(1) and 227.41(1).  
2. The Commission has authority under Wis. Stat. ¬ß¬ß 196.02(1) and 196.795 to 
consider the petitioner‚Äôs request for approval of the acquisition of ALLETE by the Partners 
under Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(3), and to apply conditions to its approval.
Background
The petitioner is an investor-owned public utility, as defined in Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.01(5)(a), 
engaged in the provision of electric, natural gas, and water service to customers in and around 
Superior, Wisconsin.  The petitioner was incorporated in Wisconsin in 1889 and acquired by 
Minnesota Power & Light Company (now ALLETE) in 1943.  ( PSC REF#: 530614 at 3.)  The 
petitioner‚Äôs immediate corporate parent, ALLETE, dates back to 1906, when it was first 
incorporated in Minnesota as the Duluth-Edison Electric Company.  (Id.)  It has gone through 
three name changes and has been doing business under the ALLETE name since 2001.  ALLETE 
stated that, for various business reasons as described in the application and set forth in the 
stipulated facts, it had decided to transition to private ownership through the acquisition of 
ALLETE by the Partners.
Proposed Acquisition
The terms of the acquisition, as characterized in the Petition, would change ALLETE‚Äôs 
ownership but not the operations of either ALLETE or the petitioner.  The petitioner stated that 
under the terms of the acquisition, Alloy Parent LLC (Parent) would acquire at closing all of the 
issued and outstanding common stock of ALLETE through a ‚Äúreverse triangular merger.‚Äù  ( PSC 
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
5REF#: 509235 at 3.)  In a reverse triangular merger, the acquiring organization creates a 
subsidiary for the sole purpose of merging with the target entity.  After the merger, the subsidiary 
ceases to exist and the target entity is the sole remaining organization.  Parent has created a 
merger subsidiary, known as Alloy Merger Sub LLC, specifically for this merger.  The petitioner 
provided detailed organizational structure charts concerning what would take place at each step 
of the proposed acquisition.  ( PSC REF#: 514114, PSC REF#: 515077.)
Under the terms of the proposed merger agreement, Alloy Merger Sub LLC, 
a wholly-owned subsidiary of Parent, would be merged with and into ALLETE.  ALLETE would 
continue as the surviving corporation and would be a wholly-owned subsidiary of Parent.  Upon 
closing of the acquisition, a wholly-owned subsidiary of CPP Investments would acquire, 
through Parent, 40 percent of the outstanding common stock of ALLETE.  GIP would control the 
remaining 60 percent of ownership of Parent through two funds identified as Global 
Infrastructure Partners V and Tower Bridge Infrastructure Partners, L.P., both of which are 
managed by a GIP-controlled affiliate as the general partner.  ALLETE shareholders would 
receive $67.00 per share of ALLETE stock.  The overall transaction value is approximately 
$6.2 billion, with approximately $3.9 billion for ALLETE shares and approximately $2.3 billion 
of assumed ALLETE debt.
The petitioner stated that all of ALLETE‚Äôs current subsidiaries and operating divisions 
would continue to exist as they exist now.  No changes to the direct ownership of the petitioner 
would result from this proposed merger acquisition, and ALLETE would remain as a standalone 
company.  In addition, the petitioner stated that there would be no changes to the existing 
affiliated interest relationships except for a new tax-sharing agreement between the Partners, 
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
6ALLETE, and the petitioner.  Commission approval for that agreement would be sought in a 
separate docket if the acquisition is approved.  ( PSC REF#: 509235 at 14.)  After acquisition, 
ALLETE would continue to have its own Board of Directors with fiduciary and oversight 
responsibilities.  The petitioner asserted that there would be representation for the petitioner‚Äôs 
utility customers regarding decisions made at the ALLETE level, as at least one member of the 
ALLETE Board of Directors must be from Wisconsin, and the Board must have at least two 
independent directors.  (Id. at 15.)  
The acquisition agreement was approved by the Board of Directors of ALLETE on 
May 5, 2024.  ( PSC REF#: 509241.)  The shareholders of ALLETE approved the acquisition on 
August 21, 2024.  ( PSC REF#: 517101.)  The petitioner asserted that the acquisition is not 
expected to have an impact on retail rates for its utility customers, and the petitioner and 
ALLETE have made guarantees that they would not pass on any of the transaction costs of the 
merger for recovery from the petitioner‚Äôs utility customers.  ( PSC REF#: 509235 at 21.)
Partners
CPP Investments is a professional investment management organization that manages the 
Canada Pension Plan Fund on behalf of the government of Canada.  CPP Investments is 
governed and managed independently of the Canada Pension Plan and at arm‚Äôs length from 
government.1  CPP Investments manages assets totaling approximately 632.2 billion Canadian 
Dollars (approximately 441.3 billion U.S. Dollars).  The petitioner stated that CPP Investments 
has investments across the energy sector in its portfolio, with a growing focus on energy 
1 The decisions made by CPP Investments are guided by an independent Board of Directors.  The government of 
Canada has no say or input into these decisions.
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
7transition and sustainability-related factors.  As part of its investment approach, CPP Investments 
has committed to achieve net zero emissions by 2050 in both its portfolio and its operations.  The 
petitioner also stated that CPP Investments intends to use its energy sector expertise and long-
term capital to support ALLETE‚Äôs management team.  ( PSC REF#: 509235 at 9.)
GIP is an infrastructure investor with experience in investing, owning, and operating 
large and complex assets across the energy, transport, digital infrastructure and water and 
wastewater sectors.  GIP manages assets totaling approximately $115 billion, and its portfolio 
companies employ over 116,000 people.  Similarly, the petitioner stated that GIP would bring its 
sector and operational expertise along with capital investment to support ALLETE‚Äôs 
management team and its commitment to decarbonize its system.  (Id. at 11.)
As noted in the petition, GIP entered into and finalized a transaction where BlackRock, 
Inc. (BlackRock) would acquire 100 percent of the limited liability company interests of GIP.  
BlackRock now has an indirect interest in the general partnerships that control each of the GIP 
funds that control ownership of Parent.  The petitioner maintains that GIP would continue to be 
the fund manager and that strategic and day-to-day operations of GIP, including the funds that 
are investing in ALLETE, would continue to be managed as they were beforehand.  (Id. at 13.)
Opinion
Requested Declaratory Rulings
The petitioner requested two declaratory rulings from the Commission in this proceeding.  
The first is for a ruling that no approval is required for the proposed transaction because both 
ALLETE and the transaction are exempt from the WUHCA.  The second is for a ruling that 
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
8ALLETE and the holding company resulting from the proposed transaction, if approved, would 
be exempt from the WUHCA under Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(8) subsequent to the transaction.  
Wisconsin Stat. ¬ß 196.795(8)(a) states, ‚ÄúThis section does not apply to any holding 
company which was organized or created before November 28, 1985, and which was not 
organized or created by or at the direction of a public utility.‚Äù  Utilities that meet the 
requirements of this provision are referred to as ‚Äúgrandfathered.‚Äù  The petitioner requested a 
finding that ALLETE is exempt under this provision, and thus the proposed transaction does not 
require Commission approval, stating that ‚ÄúALLETE is not, and has not been, subject to 
regulation‚Äù under this exemption.  In the alternative, the petitioner asserted that, even if 
ALLETE is not ‚Äúgrandfathered,‚Äù the proposed transaction is exempt from Commission approval 
under Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(3).  Wisconsin Stat. ¬ß 196.795(3), or the ‚Äúmerger provision,‚Äù 
provides that: 
. . .[n]o person may take, hold or acquire, directly or indirectly, more than 10% 
of the outstanding voting securities of a holding company, with the 
unconditional power to vote those securities, unless the [C]ommission has 
determined, after investigation and an opportunity for hearing, that the taking, 
holding or acquiring is in the best interests of utility consumers, investors and 
the public.  This subsection does not apply to the taking, holding or acquiring 
of the voting securities of any holding company existing before November 28, 
1985, if such holding company is a company which provides public utility 
service.
(Emphasis added.)
Parties are not entitled to declaratory relief.  Any action taken by the Commission in 
response to a petition for a declaratory ruling is discretionary.  ‚ÄúAny agency may, on petition by 
any interested person, issue a declaratory ruling with respect to the applicability to any person, 
property, or state of facts of any rule or statute enforced by it.‚Äù  (Emphasis added.)  Wis. Stat. 
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
9¬ß 227.41(1).  A declaratory ruling is not afforded as a matter of right.  Wisconsin Fertilizers Ass‚Äôn 
v. Karns, 39 Wis. 2d 95, 107, 158 N.W.2d 294, 300 (1968).  When the Commission declines to act, 
it does not deny the petition; rather, it exercises its discretion to make no ruling at all.
The Commission has seldom explicitly declared whether a specific holding company is 
exempt under Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(8).  In docket 1330-DR-100, it issued a declaratory ruling that 
the holding company then known as Stora Enso Consolidated Papers, Inc. (Stora Enso) would 
succeed to the ‚Äúgrandfathered‚Äù status then held by Consolidated Papers, Inc. (Consolidated) 
following a merger, implicitly acknowledging that Consolidated had previously been 
‚Äúgrandfathered‚Äù and stating that Stora Enso would hold that status after closing.2  This ruling 
represents an exception to standard Commission practice, and the Commission has not issued 
another such ruling in the twenty-five years since.  
The petitioner asserted that a declaratory ruling regarding ALLETE‚Äôs status would 
‚Äúeffectively preserve the regulatory status quo.‚Äù  ( PSC REF#: 534486 at 9.)  In declining to issue 
the requested declaratory ruling, the Commission does exactly that: it preserves the status quo, 
consistent with its prior practice.  See Petition by NewPage Holding Corporation, Stora Enso 
Oyj, Stora Enso North America, Inc., Stora Enso North America Corp., and Consolidated Water 
Power Company For Declaratory Ruling, and Required Approvals, if any, for the Sale of Stora 
Enso North America, Inc., Final Decision at 6, Docket 1330-DR-101, December 11, 2007 
(declining to ‚Äúdeviate from the status quo‚Äù and extend the WUHCA exemption to a new entity 
2 Petition of Consolidated Papers Inc., and Consolidated Water Power Company, Stora Enso Oyj, and Stora Enso 
Acquisition Inc., for Declaratory Ruling Regarding the Exemption of Stora Enso Consolidated Papers From 
Regulation as a Holding Company Pursuant to Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(8), Final Decision, Docket 1330-DR-100, 
August 1, 2000.
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
10not previously explicitly ruled exempt).  The issuance of such a ruling, either affirming or 
refusing ‚Äúgrandfathered‚Äù status to ALLETE, would alter that status quo.
The Commission has previously considered the application of the merger provision to a 
transaction in which a ‚Äúgrandfathered‚Äù holding company was acquired by an out-of-state entity.  
In that docket, the holding company, SENA, had explicitly been ruled exempt from the WUHCA 
in its entirety under Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(8)(a).  However, the acquisition of SENA by an entity 
that did not ‚Äúprovide public utility service‚Äù was not exempt from the WUHCA.3  The 
Commission stated that, despite SENA‚Äôs exemption, the company acquiring it was not exempt 
from the merger provision because it did not ‚Äúprovide public utility service.‚Äù  That decision did 
not address whether ‚Äúpublic utility service‚Äù was limited to service provided in Wisconsin.
The petitioner‚Äôs request for a declaratory ruling that the merger provision does not apply 
to this transaction could have effects that are not limited to the facts presented here.  The 
petitioner calls upon the Commission to declare, in a novel statutory interpretation, that ‚Äúpublic 
utility‚Äù in Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.01(5) refers solely to Wisconsin companies, but that ‚Äúpublic utility 
service‚Äù in Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(3) does not.  The issuance of such a ruling risks exceeding the 
Commission‚Äôs Wis. Stat. ¬ß 227.41(1) declaratory ruling authority.  The requested declaratory 
rulings and transaction approval are two discrete and independent determinations.  The 
Commission is not practically or statutorily required to approve either of the declaratory ruling 
requests before it approves the request for approval of the transaction.
3 See Petition by NewPage Holding Corporation, Stora Enso Oyj, Stora Enso North America, Inc., Stora Enso North 
America Corp., and Consolidated Water Power Company For Declaratory Ruling, and Required Approvals, if any, 
for the Sale of Stora Enso North America, Inc., 1330-DR-101, Final Decision, p. 5.
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
11The Commission declines to grant the requested declaratory relief.  The Commission‚Äôs 
decision is consistent with its resolution of previous dockets considering transactions under the 
WUHCA.  In line with past practice, the Commission takes no action regarding both of 
petitioner‚Äôs declaratory ruling requests and instead exercises its authority under Wis. Stat. 
¬ß¬ß 196.395, 196.40, and 196.795 to address the proposed transaction specific to its facts and 
circumstances.
The Commission‚Äôs practice in prior dockets has been to exercise its authority under Wis. 
Stat. ¬ß¬ß 196.395, 196.40, and 196.795 to address transactions involving holding companies on a 
case-by-case basis.4  This approach has enabled the Commission to apply various financial 
conditions to its approval of such transactions as appropriate to the facts presented, without 
necessitating the issuance of a declaratory ruling.  Although the Commission is not bound by its 
prior decisions , Board of Regents of Univ. of Wisconsin Sys. v. Wisconsin Pers. Comm‚Äôn, 103 
Wis. 2d 545, 552, 309 N.W.2d 366, 369 (Ct. App. 1981) (Wisconsin rejects the application of the 
doctrine of res judicata to the proceedings of an administrative agency), its prior decisions are 
evidence of its consistency in declining to issue declaratory rulings in similar cases.  Consistent 
with its previous practice, the Commission declines to issue a declaratory ruling as to whether 
the proposed acquisition of ALLETE requires approval under the WUHCA and whether or not 
ALLETTE and its holding company system would retain an exemption under the WUHCA 
following the acquisition.
4 See, e.g., Petition by NewPage Holding Corporation, Stora Enso Oyj, Stora Enso North America, Inc., Stora Enso 
North America Corp., and Consolidated Water Power Company For Declaratory Ruling, and Required Approvals, 
if any, for the Sale of Stora Enso North America, Inc., Docket No.1330-DR-101, 2007 WL 4632141.
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
12Approval of the proposed transaction under Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(3).
In the event the Commission declined to give the requested declaratory rulings, the 
petitioner requested that the Commission provide the necessary authorizations for the 
transaction.  The Commission has significant expertise and experience in interpreting the statutes 
it is charged with enforcing, including Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(3), the merger provision.  As noted 
above, this provision requires that the Commission determine whether or not the acquisition of 
ALLETE is in the best interests of utility consumers, investors, and the public.  While the 
petitioner disputes the applicability of this statute to the proposed transaction, it has provided the 
information that would be required under the merger provisions of Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795(3).
In the May 21, 2015 Final Decision in the application of Wisconsin Energy Corporation 
for approval to acquire the outstanding common stock of Integrys Energy Group, Inc. in docket 
9400-YO-100 ( PSC REF#: 236761 at 9-10.), the Commission held that the phrase ‚Äúbest 
interests‚Äù requires more than a finding that no harm will result from the transaction.  Instead, the 
phrase ‚Äúbest interests‚Äù requires a finding that some affirmative benefits will result from the 
transaction.  Second, the Commission held that an ‚Äúacquisition must be independently, not 
aggregately, in the best interests of utility consumers, investors, and the public.‚Äù  Id. at 10.  
Third, the Commission held that it would evaluate the ‚Äúmagnitude, timing, and certainty of [an 
acquisition‚Äôs required] benefits‚Äù on a case-by-case basis.  Id.  
The Commission applied this same evaluation to the application of Fortis Inc., ITC 
Holdings Corp., and ITC Midwest LLC, for approval of a holding company acquisition in docket 
9400-YO-101 ( PSC REF#: 292745), and to the most recently evaluated corporate merger of 
Consolidated Water Power Company in docket 1330-EI-102.  ( PSC REF#: 433415.)  In the Final 
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
13Decisions for both of these dockets, the Commission found that the requests met the ‚Äúbest interest‚Äù 
standard because they provided the applicants with greater access to capital and resources to grow 
and maintain utility infrastructure.  The Commission applied this same standard of review to the 
request for approval of the proposed acquisition transaction in this docket.
One of the key economic benefits cited by ALLETE President Robert Sandstrom in this 
proposed transaction is the ‚Äúready access to needed capital‚Äù that private ownership will offer 
over the current public ownership structure.  ( PSC REF#: 509244 at 3.)  Additionally, the 
petitioner utilized its Stipulation of Facts and Waiver of Hearing filing, which identified 
uncontested facts with which all parties agree, to reiterate the likely benefits to the petitioner‚Äôs 
customers.  ( PSC REF#: 530614.)  The parties stipulated that the sector experience and readily-
available capital provided by the Partners would be realized by ALLETE and flow to the 
petitioner and its customers if the transaction takes place, and that these benefits would support 
ALLETE‚Äôs ‚ÄúSustainability-in-Action‚Äù strategy as ALLETE continues its transition to renewable 
and clean energy.  The parties stipulated that ALLETE‚Äôs internal operations alone would not 
generate enough of the cash flow needed to fund the required capital investments of the 
transition to cost-effective and renewable sources of energy, and the petitioner asserted that 
access to the additional capital is necessary to meet ALLETE‚Äôs sustainability and 
decarbonization goals, which benefit customers and the public.  ( PSC REF#: 509235 at 32-33; 
PSC REF#: 530614 at 7-8.)
The parties also stipulated that the proposed ownership structure would diminish the 
burdens associated with the financial regulatory proceedings and equity-holder expectations 
ALLETE is subject to as a publicly traded company.  ( PSC REF#: 530614 at 7.)  The stipulated 
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
14facts identified that this may allow for lower risk and greater efficiency in meeting funding needs 
by providing timely access to capital and allowing ALLETE to avoid raising public equity during 
a valuation disruption.  Id.  These benefits would enhance the company‚Äôs goal of being a leader 
in clean energy investment.  Id.  The petitioner asserted that access to capital with lower potential 
risk than is currently available to ALLETE is likely to produce long-term benefits through access 
to lower-cost capital.  (Id. at 8.)  Those benefits, when realized, would be passed on to 
customers.  (Id.)  
The impact of that potential customer benefit is less likely to be evident as opportunity, or 
procedural, efficiencies within the business‚Äô operations trickle down to customers.  Often, 
reduced cost of capital from more efficient equity/debt solicitation is cited as a potential 
customer benefit in a ‚Äútake-private‚Äù transaction such as this.  Although economic benefits for 
customers are less likely to be evident or to materialize, the proposed ownership structure is 
unlikely to materially impair the economic standing of the petitioner‚Äôs customers.  The petitioner 
represents a small ALLETE footprint in Wisconsin and is unlikely to be influential in the capital 
funding decisions made by the new private entity, of which the vast majority is based in 
Minnesota.  Additionally, CPP Investments is a pension plan sponsor for the government of 
Canada, though at an arm‚Äôs length.  CPP Investments‚Äô mandate is set out in legislation and aims 
‚Äúto maximize long-term investment returns without undue risk, considering the factors that may 
affect the funding of the Canada Pension Plan and its ability to meet its financial obligations.‚Äù  
Relative investment risk aversion as a government-associated entity is an inherent feature of this 
new ownership structure and provides some reassurance of financial stability and consistency for 
customers post-transaction.  
Docket 5820-DR-100
 
15The partners also stipulated that the proposed acquisition would not have any impact on 
the Commission‚Äôs current oversight and regulation of the petitioner and the ALLETE holding 
company system.  Under the proposed merger, there would be no changes to the direct 
ownership of the petitioner, and ALLETE would remain as a standalone company.  
Based on the facts and circumstances presented in this docket, the Commission approves 
the proposed merger under all relevant provisions of Wis. Stat. ¬ß 196.795 subject to the 
conditions.  To enable the Commission to gather information on customer benefits identified by 
the petition, the Commission finds it is reasonable to impose a number of reporting requirements 
as identified in the Order conditions below.  As detailed in the Stipulation, ALLETE had made 
commitments and agreements involving the following: commitments to regulatory requirements 
and structure; commitments to current services, operations, and management structure; 
commitments to local workers; commitments to the Superior area; commitments regarding 
acquisition costs; and commitments to corporate separateness (ring-fencing).  ( PSC REF#: 
530614 at 8-14.)  These types of commitments further reinforce the requirements under Wis. 
Stat. ¬ß 196.795(5) and are similar to conditions imposed by the Commission in other merger or 
acquisition dockets.  Accordingly, the Commission finds it reasonable to impose additional 
record keeping, reporting, and other requirements as detailed in the Order conditions below.

PARTY TO BE NAMED AS RESPONDENT
The following notice is served on you as part of the Commission‚Äôs written decision.  This general 
notice is for the purpose of ensuring compliance with Wis. Stat. ¬ß 227.48(2), and does not 
constitute a conclusion or admission that any particular party or person is necessarily aggrieved or 
that any particular decision or order is final or judicially reviewable.
PETITION FOR REHEARING
If this decision is an order following a contested case proceeding as defined in Wis. Stat. 
¬ß 227.01(3), a person aggrieved by the decision has a right to petition the Commission for 
rehearing within 20 days of the date of service of this decision, as provided in Wis. Stat. ¬ß 227.49.  
The date of service is shown on the first page.  If there is no date on the first page, the date of 
service is shown immediately above the signature line.  The petition for rehearing must be filed 
with the Public Service Commission of Wisconsin and served on the parties.  An appeal of this 
decision may also be taken directly to circuit court through the filing of a petition for judicial 
review.  It is not necessary to first petition for rehearing.
PETITION FOR JUDICIAL REVIEW
A person aggrieved by this decision has a right to petition for judicial review as provided in Wis. 
Stat. ¬ß 227.53.  In a contested case, the petition must be filed in circuit court and served upon the 
Public Service Commission of Wisconsin within 30 days of the date of service of this decision if 
there has been no petition for rehearing.  If a timely petition for rehearing has been filed, the 
petition for judicial review must be filed within 30 days of the date of service of the order finally 
disposing of the petition for rehearing, or within 30 days after the final disposition of the petition 
for rehearing by operation of law pursuant to Wis. Stat. ¬ß 227.49(5), whichever is sooner.  If an 
untimely petition for rehearing is filed, the 30-day period to petition for judicial review commences 
the date the Commission serves its original decision.5  The Public Service Commission of 
Wisconsin must be named as respondent in the petition for judicial review.
If this decision is an order denying rehearing, a person aggrieved who wishes to appeal must seek 
judicial review rather than rehearing.  A second petition for rehearing is not permitted.
